No fewer than 24 persons were reportedly kidnapped and unspecified number of cattle and other domestic animals rustled, as bandits attacked a mosque in Tudun Amada village, Giwa Local Government Area of Kaduna State. The incident, according to sources took place around 8pm on Thursday after the evening prayer. Meanwhile, Kaduna State Police Command’s spokesman could not confirm the incident when contacted. He said he was trying to establish contact with the Divisional Police Officer in charge of the area and promised to get back to our correspondent. Sources from the village however told journalists that the gunmen in their large numbers invaded the community during evening prayer (Ishai prayer).   Why I want to be Benue’s next governor, by Aondoakaa     2023: On the consultation trail with Asiwaju Bola Tinubu     Qatar 2022: only the best for Eagles   Read Also: Gunmen kill two at Anambra petrol station According to the sources, “The bandits surrounded the mosque and abducted 14 people. They also carted away an unspecified number of cattle from Tudun Amada village, still in Giwa. “The bandits divided themselves, while some were operating at the mosque, others moved from house to house thereby abducting more than 10 women. Some of them were, however, busy carting away domestic animals such as cows, sheep and goats numbering hundreds.” It was gathered that, as at Friday evening, some of the abducted people had regained freedom. It was however not clear whether ransom was paid for their freedom or they escaped from their captors’ den.